element_texts.text: Septr 16th  Antwerp, a fortified city when we awoke this morning. we were in the Schet & at 8 o'clock landed at Anvers & put up at the Hotel de St Antoine from whence we went to see the cathedral, the museum? or the picture gallery where we saw we saw many paintings of Rubens one of the largest on canvas in the world from the bible chapter & he took up his bed & walked.  Some of Van Eyck & band the most of which were very pretty. L'Eglise de St Jaques & many other places that I do not recollect at present. At the cathedral we saw 2 large pictures by Rubens which were taken to Paris during the Revolution one of which represents the descent from the cross this is to the right as you face the altar on one of the folding door is represented the salutation of the Virgin + the other the presenting of our infant Jesus in the Temple   This picture is the most celebrated of Rubens   We went up the tower of this cathedral which has I think 548 steps from which we saw nothing but a perfect mass of roofs

Wednesday 19
left Bassano at 8 oclock in the morning + at 10 it began raining + did not cease until we arrived at Mestre before which one of the horses in the charriot fell down twice but no one sustained any injury from it though the Postilions leg was caught + he was held down until one of others went to his assistance  We reached Mestre at [?3?] oclock and left it as soon as Gondolas could be procured for our large party and the carriages could be attended to for they were left there until we leave this; our two Gondolas were rowed by 4? Men each, + after  w long hours (for it was very wet & disagreeable, which made time pass more heavily) we were landed safely at the Hotel Lion Blanc which is sittuated upon the Canal Grande + from which we have a nice view of the old but fine buildings

Thursday 20
were all up very late this morning breakfasted at 9 oclock + went out in Gondolas which we had opened. My Aunt, Mrs Bathurst her two children + the Saquais? deplace in one + Miss  Seyb?, Mary, Brother R + I in another.  We first went to see the Doges Palace where we saw some beautiful pictures by Ancient artists the first rooms Sala del Maggior Consiglio was magnificent so very large. I think 154 feet long + 74 broad. The walls are decorated by some of the paintings above mentioned + the most remarkable are 1st Paradise, by Tintoretto; which is said to be the largest picture in the world on canvas  74 feet in length it is a map of confusion & I suppose this is in a measure caused by cleaning + time 2nd Paolo Veronese. The Pope Alexander 3,  discovered by the Doge Ziani + the senate in the convent of La Carita where he had concealed

himself, when flying from Frederic 2nd in 1777. in this chamber are most of the Portraits of the Doges excepting Marino Falieri whose portrait is no where to be seen. (the rest of the portraits are in a room near) there is also a map of the ancient continent to be seen which is very curious, there are some very pretty paintings on the ceiling. this room + some adjoining contain a very extensive libraryof 801,400 Vols. which the public are allowed to use with permission. We also saw the senate chamber which Napoleon had repaired for his use after taking Venice + then the next room in which the Doge's held their private counsils the seats were of red leather cushions. we all sat in the Doges seat thence to the chamber where 3 inquisitors held their tribunals. three corners held their thrones or seats on returning we saw a hole which was formerly filled by a lions mouth of marble in which were thrown all the

petitions or complaints which the public wished to be noticed by the senate these lions mouths were placed in different chambers the stair case ^by which you enter the Doge's palace is very grand + is called the Scala dei Giganti. Some say that Marino Falieris head was cut off here + that it bounded to the bottom of the stair case but Murray says it was not in existence at that time. from thence we came to the Hotel had dinner + went to see the church Sta. Maria della Salute which was begun in ^ 1632 a thanksgiving after the cessation of the great pestilence, in which 60,000 of the inhabitants are said to have died. There are some beautiful pictures here. the one which I liked best was the Descent of the Holy Ghost by Titian when he was about 74 years old. There is a most beautiful candelabrum of bronze on the left hand side as you approach it the Alter piece is of marble + I think it very pretty - from that we

went to San Giorgio Maggiore; this church I did not like so much. The choir has most beautifully carved backs to the seats of wood it is done by a man by the name of        this church was once a part of convent 
Friday the 21st went to the Academia Academy which has some very pretty pictures indeed in it the first room has a picture of the Assumption of the Virgin in it by Titian; which looks very fresh indeed + is thought usually very beautiful in another room was a very very pretty picture, also by Titian, of Our Saviour in the Temple when his mother + Joseph came back in search of him (the disputing of the Doctors) in the adjoining room was a new picture very pretty painted for the Austrian  The subject (the father the Doge banishing his son) + the Mother + I think her 2 daughters are trying to

console her. from thence to the Royal Palace which contains very little worth seeing the rooms are very clean + comfortable but nothing like a Royal palace very few pictures I liked at all; thence home to dinner. Went after dinner with Allen  Miss Seyb + Mary to row it was very cold + disagreeable nevertheless we had some fun in laughing at ^ + about different things &c  after tea we waltzed, danced reels &c  At the Academy we saw in the Presidents chamber over his chair a vase which contains the right hand of Canova. This was done at his request + the instrument (a small chisel I think) is placed under it   
P1  The picture of our savior in the Temple as I have denoted it and incorrectly is the presentation of the Virgin + the priests at the top of the staircase awaiting her. Saturday the 22 - went to the Palazza Barbarigo where a very pretty picture of the Virgin is to be seen by Titian there are copies of it they are for sale I think there are

some others very pretty from thence to Palazzo Emo; A few ? which contains some beautiful pictures by modern artists; 2 very fine Statues of Hector + Ajax, by  Canova - then [crossed out: we went to dinner]  after to San Sebastiano the burial place Paolo Veronese his tomb consists of a bust only; there is a very pretty picture by him of the crucifixion, another of the Virgin + child, and other very pretty pictures. dined + went to Il Santissimo Redentore, built after the staying of the plague of 1576 a very little to be seen that I liked inside but the outside from my recollection is very pretty - there is a convent attached to it + we saw two Monks in the Sacristy there are 3 pictures of 1st 2nd & 3rd styles of - I do not remember the name also a number of monks heads of wax the man told us that any of them who acted very well their heads were moulded of wax + placed there - it is thought to be very fine architecture - went to San Marco, it is a most splendid church + the ceiling

is all of Mosaic + the figures are so very pretty I there saw 4 Alabaster pillars transparent which are said to have been brought from the Temple at Jerusalem. The door to the sacristy is of bronze upon which it is said Sansovino exercised his skill for 20 years the subject is the Death + Resurrection of our Lord. Also a large baptismal font of marble - at a side alter there is a pillar of black porphery + it is said there is no other like it. Also went to the Palazza Correr where we saw many pretty things of all sorts + kinds but much that I did not care for a great many ancient instruments of war + many models of Canovas statues.
Sunday the 23
Heard English service in a private dwelling house; after went to the Academy again brother Robert did not go to church + Mrs Seyb + Mary returned immediately to Hotel + as soon as we saw the

paintings we returned also to know if none of them would accompany us but only Mary would do so + we then went to the church of the Frari, or Sta. Maria Gloriosa dei Frari; designed about 1250. here we saw the Monument of the Doge Nicolo Tron, who died in 1472 it is beautiful but there are so many that I cannot describe them aposite is the ^ also splendid monumment of the Doge Foscari, they are both by Bregni, with some assistance from other artists; (this latter Doge is the same of which Lord Byron mentions in his tragedy) he died Oct 30 1457. this monument was erected by his grandson Nicolao (son of the unfortunate Giacomo) who filled several several important offices in the republic between 1480 + 1501. then the Monument of the Doge Giovanni Pesaro (who died 1658) it is supported by very immense black marble Moors or negroes dressed as it were in white marble with their black elbows + knees shewing through

the vents of their white trousers + jackets. in the center sits the Doge. By the side of this is the monument of Canova after his own design for that of the Archduches Christina at Vienna; it is in the shape of a pyramid of white marble with doors of bronze which are open + several figures are apparently entering - Titian is buried here (he died in 1575 aged 99 years) where his body is buried, there is only a plain slab to mask - we saw many pictures but only a few that I liked much.

Monday 24 at Padue
left Venice at half past 10 in the rain. however it ceased before we got to the mestre + we walked to the Hotel where we had luncheon then set off for Padue where we arrived at 4 oclock + went immediately to the university where we saw the statue of the celebrated Elena Lucrezia Cornaro Piscopia, who died, 1684 aged 48. She spoke hebrew, Arabic, Greek, Latin, Spanish and French. In addition to her native tongue all with great fluency + was also a tolerable poet etc, an excellent musician, wrote mathematical + astronomical dissertation, and received a doctors degree from the university. she died unmarried, having refused every offer however advantageous. Thence to the Palazzo della ragione built by Pietro Cozzo between 1172 + 1219, the hall is about 260 feet long + 80 broad, + as much in height the roof is said to be the largest, unsupported by pillars, in the world the wall is covered with paintings & from each side you have a view of the markets - from thence to the cathedral (or St. Anthony)

48
this church is very beautiful though not so gaudy as many you see; the tomb of St. Anthony is surrounded by silver & gilted gold lamps which are burning constantly there are also 2 immense candlesticks of silver one weighing 1607, the other 1450, each supported by beautiful marble cherubs they were indeed very pretty by the side of the high altar is a beautiful great candelabrum of bronze executed by Andrea Riccio, ten years of his labour were bestowed there are very pretty monuments here also--after to Santa Cristina but it was too dark to see anything; in going there we saw a very pretty public walk surrounded by statues of Generals, bishops etc then to the Hotel--we passed by the beautiful Cafe Pedrocchi--had dinner & very nice rooms. Tuesday--25th--Ferrara--Left Padua during the rain at 8 oclock and arrived at Ferrara at 7 oclock after having been detained first in crossing the Adige, a short time, & then the Po, by which we lost an hour we crossed these rivvers in ferry boats &

49
Hotel St. Inarco--
Wednesday 26th Bologna--Intended leaving Ferrara at 8 oclock but not being able to get post horses we determined to wait until 10 hoping they would arrive, during this time we went to the Library where we saw the tomb of Ariosto & his bust also some of his poetry as well as that of Tapo, it was in their handwriting also the inkstand & armchair of the former both of which looked well worn & particularly the latter, then saw a bible of 14 century printed with a pen & it contained small pictures & one particularly struck the attention of us all it was God taking the rib from Adam's side & forming woman the appearance was very singular indeed from thence to a church where I saw nothing of consequence 
then to the Hospital to see the prisons in which Tapo was confined for 7 years & 2 months by Alphonsa Hippolite d'Este some said he was mad & others said not that he was only in love with the sister of A & was imprisoned by A on that account

50
thence to the castle which we only passed through & went to see the small collection of paintings which belong to it there were a few very pretty pictures--then returned to the Hotel & found that horses enough could not be obtained for us all therefore it was thought best that Miss & the maids should set off in the coach as it was the heaviest & was usually behind so off they went thinking that we should overtake them in a short time but to our great vexation & surprise 12 oclock struck, we had taken luncheon & were quite ready to set out yet the horses were wanted but a little before one oclock we were agreeably surprised by Frederic's coming up & telling us that their horses had come & would be put to, in a few minutes so at 1 oclock we were off by our carraige had 4 of the poorest animals to it I ever saw & we went on so slowly that brother Robert got down from his seat cart a ? & assisted the postilion to get them on but it was all to very little purpose

51

at last we met a postilion coming back who took off 2 of the poor beasts & put his in the place we went faster for a little while then took off another & got to the next post house about three quarters of an hour after the chariot -- we then went on very comfortably & at a very good pace but saw nothing of the coach which had gone on from one post house to another with Miss Seybs telling the Master that the courier was behind with 2 other carriages they also passed the police at the gates of Bologna by Miss Seybs finding one of the men who understood German & to whom she could explain the reason of their being without a passport. When we arrived at the Hotel it was 11 oclock & Miss Seybs had almost given us up it being so late had very comfortable bedrooms & could wish nothing better--

52
Thursday 27 Bologna -- Got up very late & breakfasted at half past 9 -- went to the Academia delle belle Arti which is not very extensive though it is thought by many to contain the finest collection of paintings in Italy -- those which I thought most of was the Massacre of the Innocents by Guido also these two pictures were most beautiful so very natural many other very pretty ones which it would take too long to mention the Artists was born at this place -- thence to the cathedral where there was nothing worthy of notice; then to St Petronio built in 1132 & repaired in 1390, it is remarkable as being the place in which Charles the 5th emperor of Germany was crowned by Clement 7th it also contains the celebrated Meridian of Capini the gnomon of which is eighty three feet in height

53
We then went to the Cabinet of Antiquities some Roman, Grecian, Egyptian, Etrurian, Northern, Southern, Eastern, & Western) utensils of every description which were singular--had a nice drive in & around the public walk it was pretty--had dinner & then went to another gallery where there were some pretty pictures by Guido & others from thence had a drive to see the arched way which extends from the Town to the St a Maria del Lucia ----- Friday 28th Covigliaio ----- Left Bologna at half past 7 Vetturini housed & mules but were very often compeled to add oxen to draw us up the hills - stopped for dinner at Lojano from thence we ascend to Pietra Mala after passing this village we saw the fires of Pietra Male, which are very singular & are said to issue constantly from a spot about 10 or 12 feet across a piece of rocky ground - a high wind extinguishes them but they light readily when it ceases the flame

54
rises to about a foot from the ground & resembles that of alcohol in wet weather they are more fierce arrived at Covigliaio at 6 oclock--
Saturday the 27th Florence Hotel Le Grande Bretagne. Left Covigliaio at half past 7 during a pour of rain arrived at Vaglia where we dined at about 12 oclock got to Florence at half past 4 & found very nice apartments ready for us. Mr Buchanan came soon after & brought a packet of letters for the party -- found Mr & Mrs Francis Scott in the same Hotel ---- Sunday 30th Mrs Bathurst the children & self went to church at 11 oclock but heard very little of the sermon because our seats were so far from the pulpit & the windows behind us (where there was a great deal of noise) were open; went by Mr. Buchanans then to Hotel for the rest of the party thence to the Boboli

55
gardens which are very beautifully ornamented with statues. after dinner we drove to the cascinia where we walked this is a very pretty + to see the numbers of carriages made me think of Hyde Park in London ---
Monday the 31st Aunt Julia + I called for Mrs. Buchanan who very kindly offered to assist us in our purchases we succeed in doing what we expected. Then after taking Mrs. B-- home Mrs. Bathurst +ventured to the Hotel for the rest of the party + we all went to the galeria imperiale which we had only time to walk through thence to dinner after which we had a nice but short walk + a nice long drive. Dined after at Mrs. Buchanans with Dr. + Mrs. Bankhead, Mr. Erskine, Mr. T Scott, a Mr. Webster, Mrs. Bathurst + my Brother -- after 2 misses Backhous came + Mrs. White besides some others the evening pleasant

56
Tuesday November the 1st
Went to the church of the Annuziata which we could see very little of (as this is all saints day) it being filled with people, from what we saw of this church I should like much to take a look at it again everything is shut up today but the churches -- thence to the Boboli gardens + up to the pavilion to get a view of the town. it was not a very extensive view but rather pretty. had dinner + went to Mr. ---- studio to see the different statues which I liked very much. He is an American + I am glad to say his work is considered among the chefs d'oeuvre of Italy. I think he is a native of Cincinnati. There we saw busts of most of the great men of America ---

63
At Rome Saturday the 12th 1842 left Roncigleone at half past 6 oclock in a mist. arrived at      where we dined at about 12 + left it at    oclock. When we were at about  miles distance from Rome we discovered that once greatest of all cities + could see St. Peters + the castle of St. Angelo -- where we entered the city I cannot describe the feelings I had + but something very melancholy + sad crossed my whole frame + I could not think that we had arrived though it was true -- I could not be seated but stood up in our carriage until we got near the gate -- I wish I were able to describe my feelings; but I cannot --- rooms were engaged at the Hotel de la Public rather nice apartments but not such as the party liked for staying in during the whole of the winter --

64
Saturday the 12th
We were up late this morning & breakfasted at half past 9 o'clock - read a little french with Miss Seyb. after My Aunt Mrs Bathurst my brother & I went to see some apartments; which all rather liked; then went back for Miss Seyb & the children & went to St Peters with which I was quite charmed & felt as if I could stand still in the middle and gaze about me at the spender & magnificence of the interior but to my great dissatisfaction the dinner hour arrived & we returned to the Hotel -- after all of the party went out in the carriage to see other apartments from thence had a nice drive on the Mt? Pincio which is very high & pretty we could see a good portion of the city from it & very pretty it was - Mr Frances Scott & family arrived today & they came up after tea & sat awhile --

65
Sunday the 13th  Had a walk with Miss Seyb & the children whilst my Aunt, Mrs B-, & brother Robert went to see some rooms -- returned with my feet quite wet changed them as soon as possible & Mrs B- Miss S- the children & myself went to the English church which is just outside of the city gates for no Protestant churches are allowed to be built, or service held within the Holy City as Rome is called -- had a most excellent sermon from a Mr French, the house I think was well filled, it was very hot, returned to the Hotel & all the party Miss Seyb & I excepted went to look at other apartments then Miss Seyb went out for a walk & I remained at home alone - however they came back to dine in a short time & after all went to St Peters with the hope of hearing Vespers

66
but only heard the finishing -- and then hurried off to see something of the ancient Rome whither we drove & saw the Coliseum the capitol & many Temples though we had not time to get out of the carriage & look about us--we came back to the Hotel & after writing some in my journal Mrs Bathurst read a nice sermon after which I wrote something more of my journal then went into y room and during the time that I was undressing Miss Seyb & I had a very warm discussion; as usual upon the subject of religion & ones reading the Bible, trying to follow it & c--(She says that she does not want my advise & will not follow it therefore I have said that I shall not trouble her by giving it) The moon shines in at our windows so very beautifully bright--

67
Monday 14th 
Breakfasted late this morning & went to Mr Forlonio's (or Duke Prince or some title) his house is perfectly magnificent at least will be when finished the floors are of marble & the ceilings most beautifully painted there we saw Canovas Statue of       which I liked very much a room also which was very beautiful indeed fitted up in the Gothic style in this Salon was a table of the Pietre Daera manufacture in marble which was much to my taste & if I were worth a milion there is no knowing how much of it I might spend now while in this once brilliant City--thence to Palazzo Chiarra Colonna where we saw a very pretty picture by Raphael of himself; a very pretty Titian; La Bella Donna; pride & vanity by Leonardo Da vinche; & some others that I do not recollect well enough but we expect to see them again -- then to

68
dinner after which Aunt Julia brother Mary Selina & Self had a drive & left some cars we went with Mr Scott who met us to look at some apartments from thence up the Pincian hill & home - read a few pages of french, with Miss Seyb recited some phrases & wrote a little then to bed the Dies House was decided upon -- Tuesday the 15th At Casa Dies
It has been 2 months exactly since we left London - My Aunt, Mrs Bathurst , my brother & I went out in the carriage to leave some cards & while the two former were paying a visit we returned for the children whom we had left engaged? with their lessons - got them & then all went to see the Villa of Prince Borghese the grounds are very nice indeed there are a number of fountains & some extremely pretty here we had

69 
a short walk all wished to see the house but on finding that children were not allowed to go in, delayed it until another time; came back to the Hotel for dinner and after went out with Mr Scott, who is still in search of apartments; then brought the children to see our apartments; Miss Seyb, Mary, Selina & I walked to the Hotel by way of the Pincian Hill & the rest followed in the carriage - had tea after walked in the garden until the carriage was announced the moon shone so beautifully bright & it was so very pleasant. We left the Hotel at half past 6 for our rooms found Frederic and the maids waiting for us we want a few days to feel quite at home -- played at whist until bed time first with Miss Seyb as a partner & after with brother Robert

70
Wednesday the 16th Remained at home (all in confusion setting to rights and making everything comfortable) until after dinner when we got into the carriage & first drove to a few shops then to the Piazza de        where we walked up & down below the capitol where there are a number of ancient Temples discovered this is all very interesting to see yet it is extremely melancholly also we walked about in this enclosure until time for locking the gates when we depart? to see the Colisaeum which we only passed through I think it would be much pretier if there were no so many altars strewed around it for they hide a great portion of the lower part of the ruins -- came home had tea & the children a bed?

71
Thursday the 17th 
Took my first Italian lesson from Signore Ameligne, with Allen, Mary & Selina--wrote some of the exercises down & immediately after dinner went to St Pierre to hear some music with which I was enchanted. there were about 15 men on the left side of the altar 3 or four of which sung most charmingly there were on the right side about a dozen voices all of which were chorus or bass but all together it was so pleasant to listen to & I think if it had not been for the standing up all the time which we had to do, I should have liked to stay & listen to them much longer; the Cardinal bishop of Rome led the service for it was Mass came back by Hotel to see Mrs Scott after tea learned some of the Italian verbs; the children played at whist had a reed? I went to bed very late

72 
Friday the 18th 
Went to St Peters at 9 oclock to see the Pope where we were veiled & not boneted He arrived at half past 10 & some of the gaurds wished to push us back but the one who was stationed before us was a german & friend to our servant & when his Holiness came into that Chapel the guard was very civil & beckoned to the 3 children to come forward where they saw very well indeed. I was next them & fared very well also; the Bishop was there again & 3 cardinals; when Mass was over they all went to the high altar & three of the priests but I know not what rank, went up to a small balcony & showed us a pice of the true cross they denominate it & the handkerchief with which our Savior wiped his face; today is the anual celebration of the dedication of St Peters the

72
high altar was ornamented with their most precious relics of Saints. how strange it appeared to me to see so many people Ladies gentemen & all kissing the foot or rather the toes, of the bronze Statue of St Peter--came home practiced my music a little & did not go out in the afternoon because it was so damp & cold went at half past 8 oclock with Aunt Julia to Lady Davy's to tea where we saw about a dozen ladies with as many gentlemen rather pleasant - came back at a little after 11 oclock & found my brother still up had something to eat & he & I sat up until about half past 12 oclock talking about one thing or other -- 
Saturday the 19th wrote & learnt some of my verbs -- after dinner all went to St Maria Maggiore where we saw 2 very pretty chapels one of the Borghese family & the other of the Sforza the former was

74
extremely so & there are beautiful tombs the one to the right on entering is of Paul the 5 who built the chapel the one to the left is of Clement the 8th of the hous of Aldobrandini who made Paul the 5 Cardinal - it is of the Corinthian order ornamented with marble I do not recollect enough of it to give a better description--from thence to St Giovanni In Laterano the name of Laterano was derived from Plautius Lateranus who formerly had a house there the obelisk in front of this church is the largest in Rome it was brought from Thebes to Alexandria by Constantine & from thence to Rome by his son Constance Sextus the 5th had it erected here its height is 115 feet without base or pedestal, its diameter 9 Near this is the battisterio di Costantino which is said to have been built by him in the 4 century to be baptized in

75
& repaired by Gregory 13th & Urbin the 8th it is of an Octagon form in a chapel to the right which by the bye no lady is allowed to enter but only to peep in is a statue of John the baptist in bronze & two of serpentine; they considered this Chapel too Holy for any woman to enter as if women were not allowed to enter Heaven -- this church was founded by Constantine the great & called the Mother church of Rome

76
Sunday the 20th went to church & heard a good sermon from Mr Hutchinson came home to dinner & after to St Peters to hear vespers went up in the galery where we saw & heard very well met with Mr Scott here came back by Mrs Scotts there we left Mrs Bathurst & Selina came as far as the Pincian hill in the carriage where Miss Seyb Mary & I got out & sent the carriage back for the rest of the party it was excessively cold--Aunt Julia read a sermon & prayers wrote some of my verb --
Monday 21st Stayed at home in the morning the girls took their first music lesson from Mr Archi after dinner though still very disagreeable & rainy. Miss S.A, Mary & Self had a nice drive, called

77
to see Mrs Scott & came back by Monte Pincio. Mr Analine? came at his usual hour half past 5 we had a very nice lesson after tea the children played at whist & I joined them for a short time -- 
Tuesday 22nd Did not go out until after dinner but read & wrote my exercises; when dinner was over we went to the Capitol & into the Museo of Sculpture the most noted statues are the Faure, in red (rosso) marble the dieing gladiator, Aggrippino the Mother of Nero, & some other very pretty a number of very beautifully carved sarcophagus's -  it was beginning to rain when we came out therefore came immediately home for all of the rest of the party to get out of the carraige excepting Aunt Julia & I who went on to pay some visits - first we

78
went to Lady Grenville where I got out She appears to be a very nice person as well as the young lady who is living with her; her name is Miss Philimone; thence went to Lady Davy's but she not being at home that was soon done with & we returned to our home & tea after which Aunt Julia went to Mrs Scotts to take tea or sit with her until 10 o'clock during that time the children brother Robert & I played at whist until their bed time -- 
Wednesday the 23 Stayed at home all day all the rest went out in the morning was very busily ocupied with my crape gown which I wore to the Prince & Princess Forlonia's ball the room was a very nice one

79
it was not so briliant as I expected it to be the band was large the musicians about 25 in number the room was painted green with festoons of curtains a number of very pretty girls there knew no one but was introduced to a Mr O Farrer, Lord Loftus & Mr Gaupen could waltz with none of them the crowd was rather amusing to see but otherwise I liked it not; how I longed for some of the agreeable partners I have had at balls in my life then I should have enjoyed it -- went at about half past 8 & came home at 12 oclock 
Thursday the 24th wrote some of my exercises & part of a letter after dinner went to the Vatican which we only had

80
time to walk through this is really quite delightful I should think on a wet day for it is so extensive it is only open twice a week & then but a short time I hope to go often & then I shall be able to write something about the different objects that are there came home & had our lessons from Signiore Armelini and after tea I wrote out my verb went to bed at 12 oclock --
Friday the 25th at home all day. Mrs & Miss Blackwood came to drink tea with us they stayed until 10 oclock-- went at 12 oclock with Aunt Julia to General Ramsy's and then to Madame Campovesi's apartment to let her hear my voice she is a very nice person & recommended a master.

81
Saturday the 26th Did not go out of the house had my first singing lesson from Signor Confitate? and liked it very much he speaks only the Italian language the children had their music lessons & after Signior Armeline came we expected Mr & Mrs Scott to tea but the weather being so bad he wrote an excuse after General Ramsy came & sat a while, wrote some of my exercises --

82
Sunday the 27th
Went to church in the morning & heard a sermon from Mr Hutchinson in the afternoon went to the Villa Pamphili Doria where we had a very pretty view a nice garden with numerous fountains & a place where I suppose the ancients must have buried their dead or rather where they must have kept the skulls & the ashes of thier dead a most curious thing to see with some singular paintings on the wall -- Had a sermon at home & went to bed late
Tuesday the 29th
General Ramsy & Madame Guistiniana called here; went to the Borghese villa to see the balloon go off but were disappointed - a very nice

83
day; the man who was to send up the balloon was very much frightened for the people in general thought that he wished to deceive them and only get their money but he pleaded innocence & said he would give them tickets to get their seats again on the day in the week following an immense crowd had collected & a number of them paid a dollar for a single seat--
Monday the 28th
Drove to the Monte Cavallo one of the houses had been broken somehow or other & they were mending it; a large fountain is near it & a very immense basin into which the water belongs to the fountain is said to be the largest piece of granite of this description in Rome

84
from thence into the ? gardens which I liked very much there were fountains which were set in motion by turning a screw & it looked like little springs bursting forth & here we saw also the summer houses in which the pope received the ladies but we were not allowed to enter the palace without permission thence to the Collonna garden where we saw the old pine which is known & spoken of as the Collonna pine it said to have been planted by Rienza it is now     years old it is going fast I am afraid for in May there was a large branch broken off during a heavy storm & on last Saturday there was one broken off also; it looks like the last of the Tribunes, really it can be seen from most quarters of the town -- here we also saw the remains of the batch of Constantine--

85
Wednesday the 30th
Rained torrents in the morning & in the afternoon all went out for a drive excepting Miss Seyb & myself who went out to walk on the Monte Pincio at night Mrs Bathurst my brother & myself went to the Prince Torlonia's, to a play performed principally by children one little creature who was said to be five years old performed her part most charmingly--
Thursday the 1st of December  I stayed at home not very well the rest of the party went to the tomb of Caius Sestus & I believe were much pleased with it --

92
Wednesday the 4th of January 
Had a most charming ball here for the children first & after for the grown up ones I was introduced to a Mr McNiven a Mr Bairche a Mr Hedley & a Mr Ridley & a Mr Stonestreet we began dancing at a little after 8 & finished at a little after one oclock & ended very well everyone appeared pleased with it--
Thursday the 5th
Went to the Palazzo Venezzia & saw some very pretty paintings & sculpture a bust of Prince Albert by Wolf & several other things which I do not at present recollect, this collection is got up by the different artists to try & make a little money to assist with the building of the Cologne Cathedral--

93
Friday the 6th
Very bad weather had both rain & snow--
Saturday 7 were invited to Mrs Percevals & Mrs Conally's but Mr Aubin came in the afternoon & brought Mrs Bathurst a key to a box for that night & as we had heard so much of Clara Novella's singing, we were rather anxious to hear her & as my brother was not well enough to go with us Aunt Julia went up to know if some of the Mr Farrers would not go & Mr & Mrs Farrer went we heard Clarra N -- in the      I liked her voice but did not think it strong enough for that Opera house which was very large --

94
Sunday the 8th
Went to church in the morning & heard Mr     preach & to St Peters in the afternoon to Vespers with which I am always pleased.
Monday the 9th
The children took tea with Lady Caroline Greville & it rained in torrents -- Mrs Bathurst & myself went to Lady Harriet Norts where we met General Ramsy, the Farrers, the Miss Walpoles, the Percevals, Mr Ridley, Mr Bewicke, & Mr Buckridge it was rather pleasant--
Tuesday the 10th
Had the Farrers, the Miss Walpoles, & Miss Perceval, Mr Buckridge, the Miss Walpoles Miss P & the Mr Farrers went to the Liffonds, we danced--

95
Wednesday the 11th
The Farrers had a tea party we met there Mr & Mrs Franks, the Percevals, the Frenches, Mr & Mrs Willis, the Misses & Messrs Greathed, the french, Mr Buckridge, Mr Ridley, Mr Bewicke, Mr Hedley Mr Repton & some others pleasant--
Thursday the 12th
We

102
Thursday the 9th February 
Did not go out of doors though it was the first bright day we have had for some time; had a nice ball here with not too great a crowd danced the first ?with Mr Milles, 2 Mr Bewicke, 3 Mr Sumner 4 Mr Hedley; the country dance with Mr Stonestreet; the next ? with Mr Ridley the 1st waltz with Mr Armitage, 3 Mr Dowell, 2 Mr Scott 4 Mr Paul Gemming a german, 5 Mr      the cotillion with Capt Grange a very nice ball made a few mistakes about my engagements--

103
Friday the 10th
I walked on the Monte Pincio with Mrs Seyb & the girls my Aunt came out after a short time & we drove into the Borghese Villa had a very time & then home; we were invited to Mrs Conolly's & to Mrs DuPree's but went to neither place My brother went to the latter--
Saturday the 11th
Had french lesson & in the afternoon brother Robert & I walked in the Villa Borghese met the Conolly's driving & Miss Littledale & walking Count Sante who bowed very politely but Mr Gemming the german turned his hed & looked not towards us-- in the evening Lymon Armeline & after to Lady Grants for a short time where we met the Somervilles the Lockhearts, Lord & Lady Morley, the Percys & Miss Warren

104
& thence to Mrs Percevals where we entered when Miss P & La Ponte were in the middle of a long peice of music which was I think very good for shewing execution but not so beautiful however Miss P- sings beautifully I think & so does La Ponte we met there the Adams the Lady Grenville & its P-, the Horts?--Don unclear Mr Ridley, the Conolly's, Mrs & Mr Nivens, Mr Stephen Lawley, & the Liffords, the Percy's, & Lockhearts Capt Grange, & Mr Hestace? some other people who I knew not it was very nice indeed--
Sunday the 12th Poured in torrents Went to church in the morning & heard a sermon from Mr Hutchinson, & Mr French read prayers a day of collection for the poor rather a crowded congregation considering the weather -- remained at home in the evening & Mrs B- read a sermon

105 
Monday the 13th
Went out with my Aunt, Mrs Bathurst, brother Robert, Allen & Mary to some shops in search of lace for Mrs B-- then left some cards & came home where first at the door we met Mrs & Mr Farrer who were going to the Vatican & asked me to accompany them but I told them I had not had any dinner & could not think of leaving the house until I had as a fit of hunger had seized they offered one some of their biscuits but hunger ruled & after dinner my Aunt, Miss B my brother & self all followed them to the Vatican

107 
Tuesday the 14th  The wind very cutting Went out with my Aunt Mrs B brother Mary & Allen to the Croce in Geruselenium. a church (one of the seven Basilicae's of Rome) built by Constantine near an ancient the view of St Giovanni in Latherano Athena is very beautiful but it was so cold whilst we were there that I did not notice particularly the church but what I saw of it I liked very much & I hope we may go there another day when it is warmer this church (St Croc in G) derives its name from a part of the crop which St Helena brought from Jerusalem & deposited there; no ladies are allowed to enter the subterranean chapel of St. Helena; nor would they permit us to enter the garden near I suppose they were are afraid that some of the poor old monks would fall over head & ears in love with us but I am shure they need not be
